At the moment, I see that two major players are competing with each other for the number of keys. This is due to the fact that subnet creators require miners to submit unique molecules, while miners cannot see each other’s responses. Therefore, the only way to provide unique molecules that don’t overlap with others is to submit many different batches of 10 molecules each. Consequently, whoever has more keys – wins.

This validation system is unfair to new miners. Every new miner should have the opportunity to buy just 1 key and test their algorithm. Currently, if a new miners buys only 1 key, they have no chance of winning – even if their molecule selection algorithm is better than those used by the miners currently competing. This is because a new miners with 1 key can only submit 1 batch of 10 molecules, which is very likely to overlap with batches from other miners – of which there are more than 200.

Moreover, due to the competition between two players, the price has risen so high that it may be prohibitively expensive for new miners. Each miner currently competing has powerful scripts for purchasing. If you open the block in which registration happens (https://taostats.io/block/5397576/extrinsics), you’ll see that the transaction registering the miner in this subnet is nearly always at the very top – usually the first one (after timestamp). This indicates that if you have a weaker script, your only option is to buy a key for 3.32 TAO (around $1000 at the moment), with zero chance of winning. And of course, for the miner who keeps winning, there’s no problem raising the price to 3.32 so that new miners with a weak script can only buy at 6.64 – or even raising it to 6.64, forcing new miners to pay a crazy 13.28 TAO just to register. It’s madness.

This is wrong and unfair, and you can fix it. All you need to do is require miners to submit not just 1 batch of 10 molecules, but many batches, each containing 10 molecules. Molecules in different batches from the same key must not overlap – otherwise, they will be penalized, as is currently the case. However, molecules between different keys can overlap.

This is actually exactly what miners are doing right now. The two major players each submit 100+ batches, with 10 molecules per batch. Currently, molecules on 100 miners from one player don’t overlap with each other, but they do overlap with molecules from the other player’s 100 miners. So the work miners do won’t change at all.

At the same time, nothing changes for subnet creators either. Right now, you’re getting 200+ batches of 10 molecules, with lots of overlapping molecules. With the new system, you’ll still receive 100+ batches from one player and 100+ from another. These batches will still overlap between players, but not within a single player – guaranteeing you 1000+ unique molecules every epoch. 

To make this system work, you only need to change the final score calculation. It should be average score of all the batches submitted by a miner. At the same time, the validator should inform miners in advance how many batches it expects to receive.

For example:

The first miner’s batch scores:
    1.    38.4
    2.    38.38
    3.    38.35
…
    100.    37.55

Average: 38.0155

The second miner’s batch scores:
    1.    39.44
    2.    39.21
    3.    39.18
…
    100.    38.26

Average: 38.88

The second miner wins.

This way, every miner only needs 1 key to have a fair chance of winning. Having multiple keys won’t provide any advantage, since each miner will just collect their best 100 batches and submit them with one key. If they try to collect another 100 batches for a second key, the average score will be lower than for the first – so it doesn’t make sense.

In this scenario, the cost of subnet registration will return to below 0.1 TAO, making the subnet competitive again.

If at some point you want to receive more molecules – all you have to do is change the threshold for how many batches you want to get. Want miners to send you 200 batches? Go ahead – if you need that. The subnet will still remain fair for new miners.

If the repetition penalty seems to be working in addressing diversity/novelty though with some unintended side effects in "repeat attacks", I wonder if it may be worth reflecting on the current winner-takes-all incentive structure instead. If a miner comes up with an algorithm that is currently winning, they have an economic incentive to mass-register and enact barriers to entry for new miners. The repetition penalty further amplifies this effect and leads to high reg pressure. From a game-theoretic perspective, the equilibrium here is an anti-competitive environment where the quality of results will quickly stagnate.

It may be worth considering shifting to a Top X (perhaps with exponentially decreasing weights) incentive structure instead while keeping the repetition penalty. This way, it is significantly more difficult for a single (or small group) of miners to "take over" the subnet and enact barriers to entry. For the long-term success of the subnet, it would be better to encourage healthy competition with continuous improvements

Trying to be constructive with some meta observations: This subnet is going around in circles. It's just one scoring model, with a scoring function that is slightly tweaked every now and then. After every tweak the strategy to find the optimum solution changes, but it is found in a relatively short time, and you see multiple teams finding the optimum within the epoch deadline. So again, the challenge is just not hard enough, whatever tweak is applied.

_But the search space is so huge, it's 1 billion compounds_ I hear you think. It's actually (/apparently/clearly) not that big. E.g. the finding that the model has a bias towards shorter molecules (see https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1345470582161936405/1352058428562079765) reduced search space by a factor of at least 10. The rotating bonds logic (that had to be high or low for good scores) added another factor of 10. This way, 1B became <10M and with enough raw compute the search space is easily covered within the epoch.

_But we solved all that in the scoring metrics_ I hear you think. Yes, you solved the known issues, but miners are smart and have probably found new ways to trim the search space down. This is not a linear process; you don't go from 1B to 990M, it's exponential (see examples above) so a good filtering metric reduces from 1B to 100M to 10M and you're back at full coverage within the epoch. Aside from filtering and adding raw compute there's also pre-computation, caching, optimization, that may all bring down compute requirements with orders of magnitude.

_What if we just keep fixing these things_ you may wonder. It will lead to the slow death of the subnet, if it's just more of the same. It's a game of cat and mouse, and the miners are obviously so good that they are steps ahead in the (meta) game.

_What if we increase X, Y or Z then?_ Imagine increasing number of compounds from 1B to 10B. One order of magnitude - it doesn't change the fundamental flaw, just raises the bar a little. Imagine increasing the number of entropy bits (e.g. avalon fingerprint replacing MACCS), again, it just raises the bar a little.

Now that we're back at "who can register UID 1 fastest" I think the circle is complete, conclusions can be drawn, and something fundamental needs to change.

So what can you do? Maybe try to make the meta-game the game. Clearly, executing the model for discovery isn't all that hard, if multiple teams find the exact same optimal solution within the epoch. Just thinking out loud: Finding a better model is a harder problem. Eliminating biases from the model is a harder problem. Better yet: identifying biases in the model is a harder problem. Optimizing the model so it executes faster is a harder problem. These are areas where miners can be pushed to deliver true improvements in the field of AI Chemistry. I'm sure they are capable of doing this (they have done some of these things already) but they will not share if not incentivized to do so.

Again, I'm trying to be constructive. The potential of the subnet is huge. The miners are good. The team seems to have all the required capabilities. But it needs to break out of this circle.
